ctory of the civil rights movement. Digging into earlier radical arguments about economic inequality across America, which King drew on throughout his entire political and religious life, Sylvie Laurent argues that the Poor People's Campaign was the logical culmination of King's influences and ideas, which have had lasting impact on young activists and the public. Fifty years later, growing inequality and grinding poverty in the United States have spurred new efforts to rejuvenate the campaign. This book draws the connections between King's perceptive thoughts on substantive justice and the ongoing quest for equality for all.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aEqualityzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aEqualityzUnited States. 0aPoor People's Campaign. 0aPoorzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aPoorzUnited States. 7aHISTORY / United States / 20th Century.2bisacsh  aactivism for change.  aafrican american studies.  aamerican civil rights movement.  ablack intellectuals of the mid 20th century.  ablack poverty.  ablack rights.  ablack studies.  acivil rights movement.  acivil rights.  aclass activism in america.  ahistory of black thought.  ainterracial efforts to fight poverty.  amlk activism.  amlks legacy.  apoor americans.  apoor peoples campaign.  apoverty in america.  apoverty studies.  aracial inequality in america.  awhite poverty.1 aWilson, William Julius, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishz978311061076508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019z9783110664232oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2019 Englishz978311061017808iTitle is part of eBook package: